data.name: String123
data.value: Face milling of a surface with programmed feed in lines over the workpiece. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point. 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. 3. The outer edges are processed. 4. The surface is lined. 5. The tool is then returned to the starting point. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String124
data.value: Safety distance: Distance between tool tip and workpiece surface for positioning on At the beginning of the cycle and at the end of the cycle.

data.name: String125
data.value: Final depth: The depth to which the surface should be milled.

data.name: String126
data.value: Delivery in Z: The maximum amount by which the tool is advanced.

data.name: String127
data.value: Feed delivery: Travel speed of the tool when moving from the safety distance to the Milling depth in mm/min.

data.name: String128
data.value: Dimension in X direction: The dimension of the raw material or the surface to be processed from the zero point in the X direction.

data.name: String129
data.value: Dimension in Y direction: The dimension of the raw material or the surface to be processed from the zero point in the Y direction.

data.name: String130
data.value: Milling feed: Traversing speed of the tool during milling in mm/min.

data.name: String131
data.value: Mill inclined surfaces with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. The machine moves the tool to the zero point and offsets it then to the starting point, which depends on the surface to be milled. 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. 3. The sloping surface is then leveled off, removing any remaining material. 4. After each movement in X or Y, there is another infeed in Z, up to the final depth. Tip: Infeed in Z determines the gradation of the area. Use radius or ball end mill.

data.name: String132
data.value: Dimension in X direction: The dimensions of the material or the milling direction in X.

data.name: String133
data.value: Dimension in Y direction: The dimensions of the material or the milling direction in Y.

data.name: String134
data.value: Angle: Enter the angle of the inclined surface in degrees here. Always specify starting from a right angle (90°) to the workpiece!

data.name: String137
data.value: Drill a deep hole. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point. 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed, Only one programmed infeed is ever drilled. The drill is then raised to break the chip. From a certain depth, the drill is raised to remove the material. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String138
data.value: Drilling depth: The depth from the workpiece surface (Z = 0) to the drill tip.

data.name: String139
data.value: Feed delivery: Travel speed of the tool when moving from the safety distance to the Drilling depth in mm/min.

data.name: String140
data.value: Drilling depth chip breakage: Infeed in Z, after which a chip break is carried out.

data.name: String141
data.value: Retraction until chip breakage: Value by which the tool moves back after chip breaking.

data.name: String142
data.value: Spout depth: From this depth onwards, the system moves back to 2mm below Z=0 after each infeed.

data.name: String143
data.value: Middle in X: The distance of the hole in the X direction from the touch point. Can also receive negative values.

data.name: String144
data.value: Middle in Y: The distance of the hole in the Y direction from the touch point. Can also receive negative values.

data.name: String145
data.value: Workpiece length in X: The length in the X direction from the touch point.

data.name: String146
data.value: Workpiece width in Y: The width in the Y direction from the touch point.

data.name: String147
data.value: Mill a metric internal thread. 1. The machine moves the tool to the center of the thread. 2. The lowering process is carried out first. 3. The thread is then machined with programmed feed. and depth milled out with a helix track. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point.

data.name: String148
data.value: Mill a metric external thread. 1. The machine moves the tool to the center of the thread. 2. Then offset in X (radius + safety distance). 3. The thread is then machined with programmed feed. and depth milled with a helix track. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point.

data.name: String149
data.value: Thread diameter: Freely selectable if it fits the thread pitch.

data.name: String150
data.value:
Thread:
Distance from thread gear to thread gear.
Corresponds to immersion in Z- in mm per revolution.

data.name: String151
data.value:
Final depth: The depth to which the thread should be milled.
Pre-drilling to (depth + 2mm) is recommended! Ideally, a drill bit that matches the core diameter is used.

data.name: String152
data.value: Offset in Z-: Distance between workpiece surface and thread. For example, a thread in a bag.

data.name: String153
data.value: Middle in X: The distance of the thread in the X direction from the probing point.

data.name: String154
data.value: Middle in Y: The distance of the thread in the Y direction from the probing point.

data.name: String155
data.value: Mill a rectangular pocket with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point (middle of the pocket). 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. An oscillating movement in X or Y is carried out. 3. The bag is then emptied from the inside out. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String156
data.value: Final depth: The depth to which the rectangular pocket should be milled.

data.name: String157
data.value: Dimension in X: The dimension of the pocket in the X direction.

data.name: String158
data.value: Dimension in Y: The dimension of the pocket in the Y direction.

data.name: String159
data.value: Corner radius: Mill corner radius. The corner radius will always correspond to the tool radius if the specified value is less than or equal to the tool radius.

data.name: String160
data.value:
just finished: If this option is selected, there is no need to empty the bag. The program assumes that there is no more material inside the bag.
Only the dimension in X/Y specified under 'Finishing allowance' is removed. The machine positions the tool just in front of the wall + finishing allowance.

data.name: String161
data.value: Finishing allowance: The finishing allowance indicates how much material is removed from the wall of the pocket must be removed in X and Y in order to obtain the desired finished size of the bag.

data.name: String162
data.value: Mill a rectangular tenon with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. A corresponding amount of raw material must be removed around the tenon, (Indicating the allowance for the raw part), the machine moves the tool to the corresponding starting point to remove the raw material around the tenon. 2. The tenon is then milled to the desired dimensions. 3. The tool is then returned to the starting point. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String165
data.value: Final depth: The depth to which the rectangular tenon should be milled.

data.name: String166
data.value: Dimension in X: The dimension of the tenon in the X direction.

data.name: String167
data.value: Dimension in Y: The dimension of the tenon in the Y direction.

data.name: String168
data.value: Corner radius: Mill corner radius. If no corner radius is specified (entry = 0), the tenon has sharp edges.

data.name: String169
data.value: Measurement of raw part in X: The allowance for the blank indicates how much material must be removed per side in X in order to obtain the desired finished dimension of the tenon. Is always >= 0. Enter the largest dimension of a side here! Tip: Just finish the tenon, enter the allowance for a small tool radius.

data.name: String170
data.value: Measurement of raw part in Y: The allowance for the blank indicates how much material must be removed per side in Y in order to obtain the desired finished dimension of the tenon. Is always >= 0. Enter the largest dimension of a side here! Tip: Just finish the tenon, enter the allowance for a small tool radius.

data.name: String173
data.value: Final depth: The depth to which the circular pocket should be milled.

data.name: String174
data.value:
just finished: If this option is selected, there is no need to empty the bag. The program assumes that there is no more material inside the bag.
Only the dimension in X/Y specified under 'Diameter of raw part' is removed. The machine positions the tool just in front of the wall + finishing allowance.

data.name: String175
data.value: Diameter of raw part: The diameter of the raw part indicates how much material must be removed from the wall of the pocket in order to obtain the desired finished diameter of the pocket. This parameter only needs to be specified if 'finish only' is enabled. Note: For raw part diameters smaller than 3 * milling cutter diameter, roughing is carried out first!

data.name: String176
data.value: Final depth: The depth to which the circular spigot should be milled.

data.name: String177
data.value: Diameter of raw part: The diameter of the raw part indicates how much material must be removed from the wall of the tenon in order to obtain the desired finished diameter.

data.name: String178
data.value: Finished part diameter: The diameter of the finished circular spigot.

data.name: String179
data.value: Measurement of raw part in X: If an allowance is specified for the blank, this material is removed per side in X down to the milling depth around the tenon. First a rectangular tenon is milled and then the circular tenon. Specifying 0 in the X and Y directions switches this option off!

data.name: String180
data.value: Measurement of raw part in Y: If an allowance is specified for the blank, this material is removed per side in Y down to the milling depth around the tenon. First a rectangular tenon is milled and then the circular tenon. Specifying 0 in the X and Y directions switches this option off!

data.name: String181
data.value: Mill a groove with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point (center of the groove). 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. An oscillating movement in X or Y is carried out. 3. The groove on the contour is then cleared out. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String183
data.value: Final depth: The depth to which the groove should be milled.

data.name: String184
data.value: Dimension in X: The dimension of the groove in the X direction.

data.name: String185
data.value: Dimension in Y: The dimension of the groove in the Y direction.

data.name: String186
data.value: Twist angle: This allows the groove to be rotated in position at a certain angle. Positive values rotate counterclockwise, negative values rotate clockwise.

data.name: String187
data.value: Mill a circular pocket with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point (middle of the pocket). 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. A circular movement in X and Y (helix) is carried out. 3. The bag is then emptied from the inside out. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String188
data.value: Mill a circular spigot with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. If a corresponding amount of raw material has to be removed around the tenon, (specify the allowance for the raw part), the machine moves the tool to the corresponding starting point in order to remove the raw material around the tenon. 2. A rectangular tenon is first milled, which is then finished into a circular tenon. Without a specification in the 'Oversize blank', only the tenon will be trimmed from the diameter of the blank to the finished part.

data.name: String189
data.value: Mill an annular groove with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. The machine moves the tool to the zero point (middle of the ring groove) and then moves it to the starting point (edge of the inner diameter). 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. A circular movement in X and Y (helix) is carried out. 3. The annular groove is then cleared out to the edge of the outer diameter. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point.

data.name: String190
data.value: Process a drilling table with programmed drilling positions. 1. The machine moves the tool in rapid traverse and at a safety distance, from the zero point to the first drilling position in the drilling table. 2. Then drill at this point with programmed feed and depth. 3. The tool is then moved again to the safety distance and the next position in the drilling table is approached in rapid traverse. Tip: Simply leave positions in the table that are not required blank.

data.name: String191
data.value: Drill a number of holes arranged on a diameter. 1. The machine moves the tool in rapid traverse and at a safety distance, from the zero point to the first drilling position on the hole circle. 2. Then drill at this point with programmed feed and depth. 3. The tool is then moved again to the safety distance and the next position on the hole circle is approached in rapid traverse. This process is repeated until all holes on the bolt circle have been drilled.

data.name: String192
data.value: Mill a seal groove with programmed feeds and dimensions. 1. The machine moves the tool to the zero point (middle of the groove) and then moves it to the starting point (inner edge of the contour). 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. An oscillating movement in X or Y is carried out. 3. The groove is then cleared out to the edge of the outer contour. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point.

data.name: String193
data.value: Drill a number of holes arranged in rows and columns. 1. The machine moves the tool in rapid traverse and at a safety distance to the first drilling position. 2. Then drill at this point with programmed feed and depth. 3. The tool is then moved again to the safety distance and the next drilling position is approached in rapid traverse. This process is repeated until all holes have been drilled.

data.name: String194
data.value: Mill a letter or lettering. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point (1st letter). 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. 3. The letter or lettering is then milled in a center path (font width = milling cutter diameter). 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point. This process is repeated until the desired depth is reached.

data.name: String195
data.value: Engrave 2D DXF data. 1. The machine moves the tool to the starting point. 2. The tool is then moved in Z with programmed infeed. 3. The individual elements are then milled in a center path. 4. The tool is then returned to the starting point.

data.name: String196
data.value: Eine Nut mit programmierten Vorschüben und Abmessungen fräsen. 1. Die Maschine fährt das Werkzeug zum Startpunkt (Nutnmitte). 2. Das Werkzeug wird dann in Z mit programmierter Zustellung verfahren. Dabei wird eine pendelnde Bewegung in X oder Y ausgeführt. 3. Danach wird die Nut an der Kontur ausgeräumt. 4. Anschließend wird das Werkzeug zum Startpunkt zurück geführt. Dieser Vorgang wiederholt sich, bis die gewünschte Tiefe erreicht ist.

data.name: String401
data.value:
Description:
NC-Tool provides simple cycles for milling and drilling common shapes. Graphical input masks and assistance make it easier to create simple ones Milling programs for home use.
The output is in standard G code!

data.name: String402
data.value:
Information:
1. The cycles are based on those from Heidenhain, but have been completely reprogrammed and optimized. Milling is always done in synchronism and there is no need for pre-drilling in pockets because the tools travel to the infeed depth on a helical path.
2. For the 'Writing' cycle I took inspiration from 'dingolovethrob'. https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1nEmfoT8EGrREhB8wdw893vRD0nuCrPLf
3. For the cycle 'Engrave DXF data' I took inspiration from 'Evren DAGLIOGLU' fetched.
Project: 'DXFImporter' / E-mail: evrenda@yahoo.com
4. This project is open source (GPL 3.0 license). Please discuss any major changes with me or inform me. E-mail: petervoigt.dipps@gmx.de
